<b>Masabcha</b> (<language wordnetid="106282651" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../450/13450.xml">
Hebrew</link></language>
: מֶ‏סָ‏בָּ‏‏חָ‏ה‎) or <it>m'sabcha</it> (sometimes called "<it>mashawsha</it>") is a variation of <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../065/75065.xml">
hummus</link> popular in <country wordnetid="108544813" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../173/9282173.xml">
Israel</link></country>
<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%221%22])">1</ref>, <country wordnetid="108544813" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../849/7515849.xml">
Syria</link></country>
<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%222%22])">2</ref> and <country wordnetid="108544813" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../771/17771.xml">
Lebanon</link></country>
.<p>

It consists of warm <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../146/57146.xml">
chickpea</link>s served in a lukewarm sauce made of diluted hummus and <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../691/289691.xml">
tahini</link>, served with minced <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../469/50469.xml">
garlic</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../478/22478.xml">
olive oil</link>, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../288/214288.xml">
lemon juice</link> and spices. A <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../529/1223529.xml">
hot sauce</link> is served on the side, or even incorporated into the dish. Being served in restaurants rather than bought pre-packaged, it is often considered a "<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../465/1241465.xml">
gourmet</link>" version of hummus.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%223%22])">3</ref></p>
<p>

The main difference between <it>masabcha</it> and hummus lies in the chickpeas' tenderness. For hummus, the chickpeas are cooked until tender, then <link>
purée</link>d with tahini and seasoning. In <it>masabcha</it>, the chickpeas go through a prolonged cooking process that renders them quite soft, and then they are gently mashed with the warmed sauce.<ref xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="#xpointer(//reflist/entry[@id=%224%22])">4</ref> In <it>mashawsha</it>, the chickpeas are coarsely mashed with a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../450/317450.xml">
mortar and pestle</link>, and seasoned with hot spices.</p>
<p>

Being a lighter version of hummus, <it>masabcha</it> can be eaten for <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../768/68768.xml">
breakfast</link> or <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../377/18589377.xml">
lunch</link>, with or without <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../789/82789.xml">
pita bread</link>.</p>

